BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
We start by simplifying the two sides.

[```\newcommand{\gt}{>}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-2-2(2x+1)\amp\gt4-(3-x)\\
-2-4x-2\amp\gt4-3+x\\
-4x-4\amp\gt1+x
\end{aligned}
```]

And now add/subtract terms to separate the variable terms and the constant terms.

[```\newcommand{\addright}[1]{{\highlight{{{}+#1}}}}\newcommand{\subtractright}[1]{{\highlight{{{}-#1}}}}\newcommand{\gt}{>}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-4x-4\addright{4}\subtractright{x}\amp\gt1+x\addright{4}\subtractright{x}\\
-5x\amp\gt5
\end{aligned}
```]

And now divide each side by [`-5\text{.}`] Since we are dividing by a negative number, the inequality sign will change direction.

[```\newcommand{\lt}{<}x\lt-1```]

Graphically, we represent this solution set as:

>> [@image(insertGraph($image_1), width=>600)@]*  <<

Using interval notation, we write the solution set as [`(-\infty,-1)\text{.}`] Using set-builder notation, we write it as [`\newcommand{\lt}{<}\{x \mid x \lt -1\}\text{.}`]

We should check that some number less than [`-11`] _is_ a solution, that [`-1`] itself is _not_ a solution, and that some number greater than [`-1`] is _not_ a solution.

[```\newcommand{\substitute}[1]{{\color{blue}{{#1}}}}\newcommand{\confirm}[1]{\stackrel{\checkmark}{#1}}\newcommand{\wonder}[1]{\stackrel{\text{?}}{#1}}\newcommand{\gt}{>}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-2-2(2(\substitute{-2})+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-(3-(\substitute{-2}))\\
-2-2(-4+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-5\\
-2-2(-3)\amp\wonder{\gt}-1\\
-2+6\amp\wonder{\gt}-1\\
4\amp\confirm{\gt}-1
\end{aligned}
```]

[```\newcommand{\substitute}[1]{{\color{blue}{{#1}}}}\newcommand{\reject}[1]{\stackrel{\text{no}}{#1}}\newcommand{\wonder}[1]{\stackrel{\text{?}}{#1}}\newcommand{\gt}{>}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
-2-2(2(\substitute{-1})+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-(3-(\substitute{-1})) \amp -2-2(2(\substitute{0})+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-(3-(\substitute{0}))\\
-2-2(-2+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-4 \amp -2-2(0+1)\amp\wonder{\gt}4-3\\
-2-2(-1)\amp\wonder{\gt}0 \amp -2-2(1)\amp\wonder{\gt}1\\
-2+2\amp\wonder{\gt}0 \amp -2-2\amp\wonder{\gt}1\\
0\amp\reject{\gt}0 \amp -4\amp\reject{\gt}1
\end{aligned}
```]

Everything worked out as expected, so our solution is reasonably checked.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

